Denoising Autoencoder

version 1.5.0 (735 KB) by BERGHOUT Tarek

BERGHOUT Tarek (view profile)

=20

  • 551 downloads

In this code a full version of = denoising autoencoder is presented.
4.4
5 Ratings

41 Downloads All time: 671" data-original-title=3D"Downloads" aria-described= by=3D"popover506129">

Updated 26 Jun 2019

License

    • Zip
    • Toolbox
  • Overview
  • = Functions
  • Examples

An autoencoder is a type of artifi= cial neural network used to learn efficient data (codings) in an unsupervis= ed manner. The aim of an auto encoder is to learn a representation (encodin= g) for a set of data,
denoising autoencoders is typically a type of autoencoders that traine= d to ignore =E2=80=9Cnoise=E2=80=99=E2=80=99 in corrupted input samples.
In this code we represent to you a denoising autoencoder with a single= hidden layer feed forward networks trained by Extreme learning machine.
This algorithm allows training and testing of any dataset with the user= defined parameters and shows the main results of both of them.

in this version noise is added randomly by frames(blocks of data) , if y= ou need any information or help concerning your deep learning projects con= tact me via: berghouttarek@gmail.com

Cite As

BERGHOUT Tarek (2020). Denoising Auto= encoder (https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/71115-= denoising-autoencoder), MATLAB Central File Exchange. Retrieved May 9, 2020= .

    ------MultipartBoundary--Fryz0vnOTDKwhilrfbxm1ugMoBp9U8aFJzNrWoCYL2---- Content-Type: text/html Content-ID: Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable ------MultipartBoundary--Fryz0vnOTDKwhilrfbxm1ugMoBp9U8aFJzNrWoCYL2---- Content-Type: text/html Content-ID: Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable Content-Location: https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/mlc-downloads/downloads/6eedff03-6a0e-48f5-8439-0cad8b4826c7/ce3a156f-9159-4b79-bb53-740f39d66910/previews/denoising_AEs_frames/html/example.html =20 example

    Contents

    • Dedication
    • Build your dataset by loading your images
    • load training data
    • load testing data
    • <= a href=3D"https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/mlc-downloads/downloads/6= eedff03-6a0e-48f5-8439-0cad8b4826c7/ce3a156f-9159-4b79-bb53-740f39d66910/pr= eviews/denoising_AEs_frames/html/example.html#9">Initialization of the Algo= rithm
    • Train = and test
    • Imp= ortant Note:
    • Illustration
    • Referances

    clear =
all
clc

    Dedication

    This Work is dedicated to m=
y son "BERGHOUT Loukmane".

    Build your dataset by loading your imag= es

    load training data

    =
In the folder directory there is a folder named 'Train', after a
dialogue box appears, choose  that folder and click choose.
    pathname        =3D uigetdir;
allfiles        =3D dir(fullfile(pathname,'*.jpg'));
xtr=3D[];       % initialize training inputs
gamma=3D[96 97];% size of each image
for i=3D1:size(allfiles,1)
x=3Dimread([pathname '\\' allfiles(i).name]);
x=3Dimresize(x,gamma);
x=3Drgb2gray(x);
x=3Ddouble(x);
xtr=3D[xtr; x];% training set building
end

    load testing data

    In the folder direct=
ory there is a folder named 'Test', after a
dialogue box appears, choose  that folder and click choose.
    pathname        =3D uigetdir;
allfiles        =3D dir(fullfile(pathname,'*.jpg'));
xts=3D[];         % initialize testing inputs
for i=3D1:size(allfiles,1)
x=3Dimread([pathname '\\' allfiles(i).name]);
x=3Dimresize(x,gamma);
x=3Drgb2gray(x);
x=3Ddouble(x);
xts=3D[xts; x];% testing set building
end

    Initialization of the Algorithm

    NumberofHiddenNeurons=3D500;  % numb=
er of neurons
D_ratio=3D0.35;               % the ratio of noise =
in each chosen frame
DB=3D1;                       % the power of white =
gaussian noise in decibels
ActivationFunction=3D'sig';   % Activation function
frame=3D20;                   % size of each frame<=
/span>

    Train and test

    During training, gauss=
ian white noise and zeros will be added to
randomly chosen frames .
The Autoencoder will be trained to avoide this type of data corruption.
    [AE_net]=3Delm_AE(xtr,xts,NumberofHiddenNeurons,=
ActivationFunction,D_ratio,DB,frame)

    AE_net =3D=20

          x: [97x6624 double]
    Ytr_hat: [97x6624 double]
    Yts_hat: [97x768 double]
    Tr_Time: 2.7924
    Ts_Time: 0.0312
     Tr_acc: 0.0778
     Ts_acc: 3.7265e-14
       beta: [500x97 double]


    Important Note:
    After completing the =
training process,we will no longer in need  To use
InputWeight for mapping the inputs to the hidden layer, and  instead of
that we will use the Outputweights beta  for coding and decoding phases
and also we can't use the activation  functon because  beta  is coputed
after the activation .
The same thing is applied on biases (please for more details check the
function'ELM_AE' at the testing phase).
    Illustration
    subplot(121)
corrupted=3DAE_net.x(:,1:gamma(2)*2);
imshow(corrupted')
title('corrupted images ');
subplot(122)
regenerated=3DAE_net.Ytr_hat(:,1:gamma(2)*2);
imagesc(regenerated'), colormap('gray');
title('regenerated images');

 Denoising Autoencoders: Learning Useful Representations in a Deep Network =
with a Local Denoising Criterion,=E2=80=9D J. Mach. Learn. Res., vol. 11, n=
o. 3, pp. 3371=E2=80=933408, 2010.
[2]	L. le Cao, W. bing Huang, and F. chun Sun, =E2=80=9CBuilding feature sp=
ace of extreme learning machine with sparse denoising stacked-autoencoder,=
=E2=80=9D Neurocomputing, vol. 174, pp. 60=E2=80=9371, 2016.
[3]	G. Bin Huang, =E2=80=9CWhat are Extreme Learning Machines? Filling the =
Gap Between Frank Rosenblatt=E2=80=99s Dream and John von Neumann=E2=80=99s=
 Puzzle,=E2=80=9D Cognit. Comput., vol. 7, no. 3, pp. 263=E2=80=93278, 2015=
